Anonymous Sat 30 Jan 2021 16:16:40 No.35945469 Report

>>35934058
A pro author could knock out 2k-4k a day, but they don't. Unless you're a romance hack paid by the unedited word, pros average between 300-1500 words a day over the massive part of a year a novel-length book takes. They have to plan arcs, do the expected writer part of the editing, and might also be working simultaneously on revisions for the previous book per their editor/publishing company.

Bubbles still filling your head?
Our most productive writefags can average 10-15k of first draft a week. Let's say they take 3 months (13 weeks) to do nothing but that first draft, and for some crazy reason decided to write like a real author - second drafts, first readers, line editing & all.
So they've got ~ 200k after 13 weeks. Takes the equivalent of 4-6 weeks of 9-5 workdays to do a complete second draft. Editing yourself? Another week or two. And tack on another week or two - each - to fine tune your pacing, dialogue, and the thousands of small inconsistencies that crop up no matter how well you imagine a story in your head. I haven't even added the time it takes for a first reader to carefully read that and address issues.

Go ahead.
Think all you want that it's possible to knock out 10k of final copy in 3-5 hours/week.

I'll lay this down
My personal plan for this year was 500k of first draft over several projects. Some are /hmofa/
It is practically a fulltime job to write and edit that much, but like the last few threads where this has been repeated - write as many days as possible with a regular schedule, try to keep a consistent quality balance between getting the idea out and being autistic about how bad a first draft can be, and realize that your not-so-motivated days will produce material that is just as good as your best days.
If it helps you to outline or track your progress by word count, do it. Don't let the eventual roadblocks in your progress depress you. Switch to another project, and eventually you'll figure things out.
Whether you're writing greentext or longform prose, it's a long journey. Whether the roughest fetish smut or the most pretentious literary /hmofa/, we all go through the same steps.
